                  <handDesc>
                     
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">Mediocre and irregular.</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black; vermilion.</seg>
                        <persName role="scribe" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10788WaldaMuse">Walda Muse</persName>Walda
                        Muse is mentioned as the scribe in the supplication formula, <locus target="#17r">17r</locus>, l.9. However, the handwriting appears to be
                        dissimilar from that of the scribe Walda Muse attested in some other
                        manuscripts (e.g., SMM-004, UM-023, MR-016 etc.); but it appear similar to
                        Ms. SMM-006.<date>Second half of the 19th century.</date>
                        <list type="abbreviations">
                           <item>none</item>
                        </list>
                        <seg type="rubrication">Nomina sacra; the name of Metropolitan ʾAtänatewos
                           (fol. 9v ls.4-5) and of King Yoḥannǝs (fol. 5r ls.8-9); elements of
                           punctuation signs and of Ethiopic numerals.
 The Trinitarian formula
                           in the incipit page of the text (fol. 1r) and the initial words of its
                           subsections.</seg>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">The broadly spaced handwriting is
                        characterized by thin and tall letters, slightly slanted to the right.
                        </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic"> - The loops of ግ and ቆ are in many
                        cases very pronounced.
                        </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h4" script="Ethiopic"> - The top of some letters is sometimes
                        extends beyond the headline: cp. ቶ on <locus target="#2v">2v</locus> l.9,
                        14r l.1; ት on <locus target="#7v">7v</locus> l.1; ግ e.g., <locus target="#8v">8v</locus>, l.8, 9v, l.1 <locus target="#19v">19v</locus>
                        l.5.</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h5" script="Ethiopic"> - The vowel marker of ይ has a hook
                        shape, particularly rounded and curved (e.g., <locus target="#2v">2v</locus>
                        l.10, 3r, ls. 4 and 9).
                        </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h6" script="Ethiopic"> - The word እግዚአብሔር is usually written
                        with ligature (ግ and ዚ, e.g., <locus target="#2v">2v</locus> l.8, 7v
                        l.3).</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
